<node TEXT="(thanks to Christian Heimes for the suggestion to make read more" ID="ID_1385455642" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="idiomatic. I&apos;ll in turn let whichever project I stole this code from" ID="ID_1767883156" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="know...)" ID="ID_422700204" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="Most of the contents are straightforward and could be gleaned from the" ID="ID_972944278" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="setuptools documentation, so I&apos;ll only touch on the &quot;interesting&quot;" ID="ID_1986509135" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="parts. Using sandman.__version__ and the method of getting" ID="ID_12937892" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="long_description (taken from the setup.py of other projects, though I" ID="ID_315210537" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="can&apos;t remember which ones) reduce the amount of boilerplate code we" ID="ID_836448037" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="need to write. Instead of maintaining the project&apos;s version in three" ID="ID_1208890066" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="places (setup.py, the package itself via package.__version__, and the" ID="ID_180811690" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="documentation), we can always use the package&apos;s version to populate" ID="ID_243119337" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="the version parameter in setup." ID="ID_517354671" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="long_description is the document used by PyPI as the description on" ID="ID_47314892" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="your project&apos;s PyPI page. As there is another file, README.md with" ID="ID_1496297090" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="almost the exact same content, I use pandoc to automatically generate" ID="ID_421191882" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="README.rst from README.md. Thus, we can simply read the file" ID="ID_758645802" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="README.rst and use that as the value for long_description." ID="ID_13278877" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="py.test (discussed below) has a special entry (class PyTest) to allow" ID="ID_496825720" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="python setup.py test to work correctly. That code snippet was taken" ID="ID_960197566" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="directly from the py.test documentation." ID="ID_1474904675" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="Everything else is in the file is simply setting values for the setup" ID="ID_191692984" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="parameters described in the documentation." ID="ID_1383388464" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="Other setup.py parameters" ID="ID_1609350682" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861">
<node TEXT="There are some setup arguments that sandman has no use for, but your" ID="ID_95057434" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="package might. For example, you may be distributing a script that" ID="ID_671166752" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="you&apos;d like your user to be able to execute from the command line. In" ID="ID_976865294" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="the example above, that script would only be installed in the normal" ID="ID_1656874313" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="site-packages location along with the rest of your code. There would" ID="ID_1041108584" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="be no (easy) way for the user to run it after it was installed." ID="ID_1347936406" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="For that reason, setup can take a scripts argument that specifies" ID="ID_1003608695" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="Python scripts that should be installed as such. To install a script" ID="ID_902433925" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="called go_foo.py from your package, the call to setup would include" ID="ID_559284644" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="the line:" ID="ID_960322806" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="scripts = [&apos;go_foo.py&apos;]," ID="ID_1701832195" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="Just make sure you put the relative path to your script, not just its" ID="ID_1616349822" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="name (e.g. scripts = [&apos;scripts/foo_scripts/go_foo.py&apos;]). Also, your" ID="ID_1567699595" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="script should begin with a &quot;shebang&quot; line with &quot;python&quot; in it, like:" ID="ID_507696261" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861">
<node TEXT="#! /usr/bin/env python" ID="ID_1929644713" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="distutils will automatically replace this line with the current" ID="ID_86785167" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="interpreter location during installation." ID="ID_195689409" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="If your package is more complex than the simple one discussed here," ID="ID_948055633" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="take a look at both the setuptools documentation and &quot;Distributing" ID="ID_26841564" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="Python Modules&quot; from the official documentation. Between the two, you" ID="ID_1138173804" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="should be able to straighten out any issues you might have" ID="ID_1497817593" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
<node TEXT="encountered." ID="ID_1805429495" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861"/>
</node>
</node>
<node TEXT="Source Control With Git, Project Management with GitHub" ID="ID_1922231425" CREATED="1406792949861" MODIFIED="1406792949861">
<node TEXT="In &quot;Starting a Django Project The Right Way,&quot; I suggest either git or" ID="ID_1029995113" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="mercurial for version control. For a project meant to be both shared" ID="ID_142163193" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="and contributed to, there&apos;s really only one choice: git. In fact, I&apos;ll" ID="ID_1157854584" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="go so far as to say that not only is the use of git necessary, you&apos;ll" ID="ID_440280132" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="also need to use GitHub to maintain your project if you want people to" ID="ID_1016334638" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="actually use and contribute to it." ID="ID_1164541405" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="It&apos;s not meant to be an inflammatory statement (though no doubt many" ID="ID_900900605" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="will take issue with it). Rather, for better or worse, git and GitHub" ID="ID_1917027167" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="have become the de-facto standard for Open Source projects. GitHub is" ID="ID_826766396" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="the site potential contributors are most likely to be registered on" ID="ID_1491673350" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="and familiar with. That, I believe, is not a point to be taken" ID="ID_1002279381" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="lightly." ID="ID_985921292" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="Create a README.md File" ID="ID_832228139" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876">
<node TEXT="The project description for repos on GitHub is taken from a file in" ID="ID_1950692352" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="the project&apos;s root directory: README.md. This file should contain the" ID="ID_1620030930" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="following pieces of information:" ID="ID_1141161416" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876">
<node TEXT="A description of your project" ID="ID_1065215367" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="Links to the project&apos;s ReadTheDocs page" ID="ID_1811863742" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="A TravisCI button showing the state of the build" ID="ID_780351537" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="&quot;Quickstart&quot; documentation (how to quickly install and use your project)" ID="ID_620403872" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="A list of non-Python dependencies (if any) and how to install them" ID="ID_1841466160" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="It may sound silly, but this is an important file. It&apos;s quite likely" ID="ID_999791664" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="to be the first thing both prospective users and contributors read" ID="ID_1027133208" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="about your project. Take some time to write a clear description and" ID="ID_1447666379" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="make use of GFM (GitHubFlavoredMarkdown) to make it look somewhat" ID="ID_1191557512" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="attractive. You can actually create/edit this file right on GitHub" ID="ID_1422365195" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="with a live-preview editor if you&apos;re not comfortable writing documents" ID="ID_862102299" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="in raw Markdown." ID="ID_81974732" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="We haven&apos;t yet covered the second and third items in the list yet" ID="ID_1585656296" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="(ReadTheDocs and TravisCI). You&apos;ll find these discussed below." ID="ID_1810845773" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="Using the &quot;Issues&quot; Page" ID="ID_1751018554" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876">
<node TEXT="Like most things in life, the more you put into GitHub, the more you" ID="ID_1816574410" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="get out of it. Since users will be using it to file bug reports" ID="ID_836217617" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="anyway, making use of GitHub&apos;s &quot;Issues&quot; page to track feature requests" ID="ID_1414661859" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="and enhancements just makes sense." ID="ID_929172102" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="More importantly, it allows potential contributors to both see a list" ID="ID_759273903" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="of things they might implement and automatically manages the pull" ID="ID_878471915" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="request workflow in a reasonably elegant manner. GitHub issues and" ID="ID_1817905842" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="their comments can be cross-linked with commits, other issues in your" ID="ID_1882131847" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="project, issues in other projects, etc. This makes the &quot;Issues&quot; page a" ID="ID_1113076990" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="good place to keep all of the information related to bug fixes," ID="ID_1523998719" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="enhancements, and feature requests." ID="ID_950711878" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="Make sure to keep &quot;Issues&quot; up to date and to at least briefly respond" ID="ID_293104393" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="to new issues in a timely manner. As a contributor, there&apos;s nothing" ID="ID_1302979741" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="more demotivating than fixing a bug and watching as it languishes on" ID="ID_396895143" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="the issues page, waiting to be merged." ID="ID_649347559" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
</node>
</node>
<node TEXT="A Sensible git Workflow With git-flow" ID="ID_507787739" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876">
<node TEXT="To make things easier on both yourself and contributors, I suggest" ID="ID_818427914" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="using the very popular git-flow model of branching." ID="ID_1527853332" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="Quick Overview" ID="ID_464264738" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876">
<node TEXT="The develop is the branch you&apos;ll be doing most of your work off" ID="ID_1744171946" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="of; it&apos;s also the branch that represents the code to be deployed" ID="ID_1216219763" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="in the next release. feature branches represent non-trivial" ID="ID_453432880" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="features and fixes that have not yet been deployed (a completed" ID="ID_1213325658" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="feature branch is merged back into develop). Updating master is" ID="ID_1305371202" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="done through the creation of a release." ID="ID_1647964683" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="Installation" ID="ID_1209347641" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="Install git-flow by following the instructions for your platform here." ID="ID_1685802987" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="Once installed, you can migrate your existing project with the command" ID="ID_775097215" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="$ git flow init" ID="ID_190346930" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="Branch Details" ID="ID_529592573" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876">
<node TEXT="You&apos;ll be asked a number of configuration questions by the" ID="ID_1048248227" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="script. The default values suggested by git-flow are fine to" ID="ID_1072035926" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="use. You may notice your default branch is set to" ID="ID_13637778" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="develop. More on that in a moment. Let&apos;s take a step back and" ID="ID_899141806" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="describe the git-flow... erm, flow, in a bit more detail. The" ID="ID_655023031" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="easiest way to do so is to discuss the various branches and" ID="ID_1837201227" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="types of branches in the model." ID="ID_272729598" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="Master" ID="ID_1197420675" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876">
<node TEXT="master is always &quot;production ready&quot; code. Commits are never" ID="ID_1908784242" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="made directly to master. Rather, code on master only gets" ID="ID_292034417" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="there after a production release branch is created and" ID="ID_184228767" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="&quot;finished&quot; (more on that in a sec). Thus the code on master is" ID="ID_1341327590" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="always able to be released to production. Also, master is" ID="ID_87643440" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="always in a predictable state, so you never need to worry if" ID="ID_669311811" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="master (and thus production) has changes one of your other" ID="ID_1252309553" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="branches doesn&apos;t." ID="ID_290958219" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="Develop" ID="ID_105428901" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876">
<node TEXT="Most of your work is done on the develop branch. This branch" ID="ID_1725515000" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="contains all of the completed features and bug fixes yet to be" ID="ID_859331108" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="released; nightly builds or continuous integration servers" ID="ID_1203672971" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="should target develop, as it represents the code that will be" ID="ID_786361873" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="included in the next release." ID="ID_48109875" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="For one-off commits, feel free to commit to develop directly." ID="ID_1847159365" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="Feature" ID="ID_230385968" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876">
<node TEXT="For larger features, a feature branch should be" ID="ID_1392782577" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="created. feature branches are created off of develop. They can" ID="ID_75110037" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="be small enhancements for the next release or further out" ID="ID_702813415" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="changes that, nonetheless, need to be worked on now. To start" ID="ID_1851787476" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="work on a new feature, use:" ID="ID_492098873" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="$ git flow feature start &lt;feature name&gt;" ID="ID_1279646829" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="This creates a new branch: feature/&lt;feature name&gt;. Commits are" ID="ID_722693551" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="then made to this branch as normal. When the feature is" ID="ID_727295465" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="complete and ready to be released to production, it should be" ID="ID_347349041" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="merged back into develop using the following command:" ID="ID_1455452667" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="$ git flow feature finish &lt;feature name&gt;" ID="ID_945496082" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="This merges the code into develop and deletes the" ID="ID_711421673" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="feature/&lt;feature name&gt; branch." ID="ID_584999986" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="Release" ID="ID_581985775" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876">
<node TEXT="A release branch is created from develop when you&apos;re ready to" ID="ID_1242144877" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="begin a production release. Create one using the following" ID="ID_727504730" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="command:" ID="ID_1504960555" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="$ git flow release start &lt;release number&gt;" ID="ID_636110068" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="Note that this is the first time a version number for the" ID="ID_1252993307" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="release is created. All completed and ready to be released" ID="ID_578758646" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="features must already be on develop (and thus feature" ID="ID_1507800530" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="finish&apos;ed). After your release branch is created, release your" ID="ID_647749625" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="code. Any small bug fixes needed after the release are made" ID="ID_404964284" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="directly to the release/&lt;release number&gt; branch. Once it has" ID="ID_226789403" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="settled down and no more bug fixes seem necessary, run the" ID="ID_1288436217" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="following command:" ID="ID_1242951119" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="$ git flow release finish &lt;release number&gt;" ID="ID_251541699" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="This merges your release/&lt;release number&gt; changes back into" ID="ID_248902559" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="both master and develop, meaning you never need to worry about" ID="ID_281485484" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="either of those branches lacking changes that are in" ID="ID_114688647" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="production (perhaps as the result of a quick bug fix)." ID="ID_366039873" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="Hotfix" ID="ID_1157536915" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876">
<node TEXT="While potentially useful, hotfix branches are, I would guess," ID="ID_90761564" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="little used in the real world. A hotfix is like a feature" ID="ID_1526141400" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="branch off of master: if you&apos;ve already closed a release" ID="ID_374390543" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="branch but realize there are vital changes that need to be" ID="ID_1864254407" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="released, create a hotfix branch off of master (at the tag" ID="ID_1471910299" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="created during $ git flow release finish &lt;release number&gt;)" ID="ID_1497502488" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="like so:" ID="ID_1855662506" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="$ git flow hotfix start &lt;release number&gt;" ID="ID_1474597275" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="After you make your changes and bump your version number," ID="ID_1587860101" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="finalize the hotfix via" ID="ID_1383965543" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="$ git flow hotfix finish &lt;release number&gt;" ID="ID_119821993" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="This, like a release branch (since it essentially is a type of" ID="ID_407890421" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="release branch), commits the changes to both master and" ID="ID_933857993" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="develop." ID="ID_1287284715" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="The reason I assume they&apos;re rarely used is because there is" ID="ID_257573335" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="already a mechanism for making changes to released code:" ID="ID_1117277518" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="committing to an un-finished release branch. Sure, in the" ID="ID_733855576" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="beginning, teams may git flow release finish ... too early," ID="ID_1496584757" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="only to find they need to make some quick changes the next" ID="ID_1052510449" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="day. Over time, though, they&apos;ll settle on a reasonable amount" ID="ID_1919285479" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="of time for a release branch to remain open and, thus, won&apos;t" ID="ID_881573032" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="have a need for hotfix branches. The only other time you would" ID="ID_398133442" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="need a hotfix branch is if you needed a new &quot;feature&quot; in" ID="ID_1242789629" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="production immediately, without picking up the changes already" ID="ID_1820104730" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="in develop. That strikes me as something that happens" ID="ID_1514128037" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
<node TEXT="(hopefully) very rarely." ID="ID_177788318" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876"/>
</node>
</node>
<node TEXT="Testing With py.test" ID="ID_1349888837" CREATED="1406792949876" MODIFIED="1406792949876">
<node TEXT="In the Python automated testing ecosystem, there are two main" ID="ID_1484716235" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="alternatives to the (quite usable) Python standard library" ID="ID_1427260725" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="unittest package: nose and py.test. Both extend unittest to" ID="ID_1067556131" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="make it easier to work with while adding additional" ID="ID_1060959727" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="functionality. Truthfully, either is a fine choice. I happen" ID="ID_947672317" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="to prefer py.test for a few reasons:" ID="ID_1394699110" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877">
<node TEXT="Support for setuptools/distutils projects" ID="ID_482803424" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877">
<node TEXT="python setup.py test still works" ID="ID_787850298" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="Support for &quot;normal&quot; assert statements (rather than" ID="ID_1253532545" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="needing to remember all the jUnit-style assert functions)" ID="ID_860559159" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="Less boilerplate" ID="ID_740614805" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="Support for multiple testing styles" ID="ID_61374921" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877">
<node TEXT="unittest" ID="ID_323182592" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="doctest" ID="ID_323408730" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="nose tests" ID="ID_1821251809" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
</node>
</node>
<node TEXT="Note" ID="ID_1136617690" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877">
<node TEXT="If you already have an automated testing solution, feel free to continue using it and skip this section. Be warned that later sections may assume testing is done using py.test, which may affect configuration values." ID="ID_1723337086" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="Test Setup" ID="ID_862759646" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877">
<node TEXT="In the test directory, wherever you decided it should live," ID="ID_538647547" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="create a file called test_&lt;project_name&gt;.py. py.test&apos;s test" ID="ID_1660813152" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="discovery mechanism will treat any file with the test_ prefix" ID="ID_1167073663" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="as a test file (unless told otherwise)." ID="ID_1728016077" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="What you put in that file is largely up to you. Writing tests" ID="ID_1743159813" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="is a giant topic and outside of the scope of this article. The" ID="ID_1665989339" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="important thing, however, is that the tests are useful to both" ID="ID_1491045926" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="you and potential contributors. It should be clear what" ID="ID_257122891" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="functionality each test is exercising. Tests should be written" ID="ID_1340792826" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="in the same &quot;style&quot; so that a potential contributor doesn&apos;t" ID="ID_579084791" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="have to guess which of the three styles of testing used in" ID="ID_1402533596" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="your project he/she should use." ID="ID_1935830430" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
</node>
<node TEXT="Test Coverage" ID="ID_1971890537" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877">
<node TEXT="Automated test coverage is a contentious topic. Some believe" ID="ID_1101734394" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="it to be a meaningless metric that gives false" ID="ID_1241846227" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="security. Others find it genuinely useful. At the very least," ID="ID_1417289192" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="I would suggest if you already have tests and have never" ID="ID_742154766" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="checked your test coverage, do so now as an exercise." ID="ID_1024788823" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="With py.test, we can make use of Ned Batchelder&apos;s coverage" ID="ID_1076691000" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="tool. To do so, $ pip install pytest-cov. If you previously" ID="ID_51027729" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="ran your tests like this:" ID="ID_647499533" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="$ py.test" ID="ID_667392351" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="you can generate test coverage reports by passing a few" ID="ID_1951793909" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="additional flags. Below is an example of running sandman" ID="ID_267923907" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="$ py.test --cov=path/to/package" ID="ID_735068618" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
<node TEXT="$ py.test --cov=path/to/package --cov-report=term --cov-report=html" ID="ID_1027653911" CREATED="1406792949877" MODIFIED="1406792949877"/>
